NVIDIA's revenues from customers spending less than $6bn a quarter is collapsing just as it becomes difficult for large customers buying billions of GPUs to raise debt. NVIDIA is almost entirely reliable on a few big customers, and I'm not sure how long they last.
wheresyoured.at/premium-how-...

images.alt:
I realize I've thrown a lot of numbers at you, so I'm gonna make this really simple:

NVIDIA's revenue is now largely dependent on four customers, and considering Meta, Google, Oracle and CoreWeave have all raised tens of billions of dollars of debt in the last year, it's safe to say that these GPUs are being bought with debt. Remember, hyperscalers buy in bulk.
Otherwise, NVIDIA is selling billions of dollars of GPUs — around 2.39GW worth by my estimates — to companies building data centers in the 25MW to 300MW range, and these projects, at best, take months if not years to energize and generate revenue.
Remember, the majority of these projects are likely debt-funded too.
And, most crucially, based on NVIDIA's sales and customer concentration, the amount of new data center builds is decreasing.
Though my modeling around revenue-to-megawatts is a little rough, there's no way to avoid the fact that diversified customers are buying less GPUs, which suggests they are building or retrofitting less data centers.

If I'm wrong, why has NVIDIA's diversified revenue collapsed? Diversified revenue has gone from $30.8 billion in Q1 FY2026 to $22.2 billion in Q3 2026 as overall revenue increased by $12.9 billion (from $44 billion to $57 billion).

This number sours further when you focus specifically on data center revenue — which, as a reminder, is 89% of NVIDIA's revenue! — which collapsed from $25.89 billion in Q1 FY2026 to $16.44 billion in Q3 FY2026.

So What Does This All Mean?
By the looks of it, NVIDIA's "regular" AI GPU customers — those building normal-sized data centers that don't require loans from multiple banks — are spending less on GPUs.
I recognize that there could also be large customers (hyperscalers) who are buying a lot of GPUs but accounting for less than 10% of NVIDIA's revenue. Nevertheless,
NVIDIA's revenues are becoming increasingly-dependent on customers that can afford to spend $6 billion to $12 billion per quarter.
Realistically, there are only a few remaining parties that can afford this:
Oracle, which is having trouble raising debt, and has created shockwaves through the stock market thanks to its increasing liabilities and dwindling cashflow.
Blue Owl, which is pulling out of helping Oracle raise debt.
OpenAI, which actually can't afford to buy anything and relies on Oracle and other parties to do so on its behalf.
Microsoft, which has pulled back on data center construction and has GPUs sitting in inventory it cannot turn on.
Meta, which had to do financial alchemy to close a $30 billion off-balance-sheet SPV with Blue Owl, which is pulling out of raising data center debt.
CoreWeave, which is an unprofitable ticking time bomb of debt that has relied upon Blue Owl to raise debt.
Google, which has just signed a deal with Anthropic to use "up to one million" of its TPUs, is working on a deal to rent TPUs to Meta, and has spent the best part of a year telling everybody how good its TPUs are — and whether they are or not is immaterial, because Google is clearly signaling it wants to spend less with NVIDIA.
Amazon, which is rumored to be investing $10 billion in OpenAI as a means of getting it to use its Trainium chips and claims Anthropic will use one million of them by the end of 2025.
Resellers like Supermicro and Dell, who do not appear to be doing sales that would suggest they can continually shift $6bn to $12bn of GPUs a quarter.

While this might seem like a formidable list, every party is making some sort of sound that says "we don't want to buy GPUs forever." Elsewhere, fewer customers are interested in (or able to afford) to buy GPUs at the rate that NVIDIA needs to sell them, likely because the flow of capital is decreasing and AI is yet to prove any actual economic value beyond selling these god damn GPUs.

If I'm wrong, then NVIDIA will need to show a rapid and dramatic increase in diversified revenue, to the tune of $5 billion to $10 billion, in its next quarterly revenue.

And we still have the problem I've been going on about for the last month: there isn't enough actual, real capacity built to house all of these GPUs, which means that the remaining customers are likely buying and warehousing them as they wait for construction to finish and power to connect.

New data center capacity is not being built at the rate that NVIDIA is selling GPUs, and it's becoming clear that banks are no longer as interested in funding the massive loans necessary to build the infrastructure to install them.

Once we turn them on, we still have no firm grasp on the actual margins behind providing AI compute — and all signs seem to point to these AI data centers being very, very unprofitable.

And then you get to the other problem — that the customers of AI compute are mostly unprofitable AI model labs providing unprofitable services to unprofitable AI companies, and the funding behind them is also collapsing.

I can truly see 2026 being the year that the bubble bursts. AI does not have the margins or performance or productivity gains that underpin any major technology revolution, and the only "innovation" appears to be in how many bankers and private equity firms can be conned into sinking money into the least-profitable software and hardware ever made.

images.alt:
NVIDIA's Customer Base Is Quietly Collapsing, Papered Over By Large Sales, With Four Customers Accounting For 61% of Revenue In Its Latest (Q3 FY2026) Quarter, Up From 30% In Q1 FY2026
According to a report from last week from Axios, there are just over 2,700 data centers either under construction or being planned in America, but, of course, the report neglects to say their potential IT load. CNBC claims that $60 billion was sunk into data center deals in 2025, but doesn't break down whether that includes GPUs, because if it does, that doesn't remotely explain how NVIDIA, who makes 69% of its revenue from America.

Yet I've done a little guesswork here. I assumed that 50% of the purchases were made by and for hyperscalers spooging their $400 billion in capex, when I can actually dig into NVIDIA's earnings and start looking at real customer concentration!

...and things get weirder when you read NVIDIA's earnings. To be clear, when it says "compute and networking," NVIDIA is referring to its data center revenue.

Q3 FY26 - Direct Customers – For the third quarter of fiscal year 2026, four direct customers with sales greater than 10% of total revenue included: Customer A at 22%, Customer B at 15%, Customer C at 13%, and Customer D at 11%, which were attributable to the Compute & Networking segment.
Okay, so that's 61% of NVIDIA's total quarterly revenue — so $34.77 billion (as in 61% of $57.006) billion) — that went to four companies? That's 67.8% of data center revenue, NVIDIA's largest revenue source!

Q2 FY26 - For the second quarter of fiscal year 2026, sales to one direct customer, Customer A, represented 23% of total revenue; and sales to a second direct customer, Customer B, represented 16% of total revenue, respectively, both of which were attributable to the Compute & Networking segment. 
Oh, so things were better a quarter ago — that's $18.229 billion (39% of $46.743 billion), or 44.3% of data center revenue.

Q1 FY2026 - Sales to one direct customer, Customer A, represented 16% of total revenue and sales to a second direct customer, Customer B, represented 14% of total revenue for the first quarter of fiscal year 2026, both of which were attributable to the Compute & Networking segment.
So, now we see the pattern. In Q1 FY2026, two customers accounted for 30% of total revenue — or around $13.2 billion, or around 33.7% of data center revenue.

NVIDIA has a massive customer concentration problem.

Q1 FY2026:
Total Revenue: $44.06 billion
Data Center Revenue: $39.112 billion
Data Center Revenue With Two Customers ($13.2 billion) Removed: $25.893 billion
Total Revenue With Two Customers Removed: $30.84 billion
Approximate MW of leftover customers: 968MW
Q2 FY2026:
Total Revenue: $46.74 billion
Data Center Revenue: $41.096 billion
Data Center Revenue With Two Customers ($18.22 billion) Removed: $22.86 billion
Total Revenue With Two Customers Removed: $28.51 billion
Approximate MW of leftover customers: 827MW
Q3 FY2026:
Total Revenue: $57.006 billion
Data center Revenue: $41.096 billion
Data Center Revenue With Four Customers Removed: $16.441 billion
Total Revenue With Four Customers Removed: $22.23 billion
Approximate MW of leftover customers: 595MW
Over time, NVIDIA's customer concentration has begun to lean heavily on hyperscalers or very large GPU purchasers. Let's break down Q3 FY2026:

Customer A - 22% - $12.54 billion - around 453MW
Customer B - 15% - $8.55 billion - around 309MW
Customer C - 13% - $7.41 billion - around 268MW
Customer D - 11% - $6.27 billion - around 229MW
These are load-bearing clients, and the loads only seem to increase with every quarter.
